story.title: The Children - Episode 6
story.storyDescription: Someone throws a brick through Kiera's window. On the attached note, it says: GIVE BACK OUR CHILDREN.

messages.text: Hey ‚Äî got my phone back. Figured this would be easier than the burner phone I was using.
The government found me. They‚Äôre bringing me back. I‚Äôve got one chance to fix things. If I don‚Äôt‚Ä¶
Just know how sorry I am and how much I love you.
They showed me footage on a tablet. The destruction‚Ä¶it‚Äôs just feeding the virus.
I need to put an end to this.
I don‚Äôt want to‚Ä¶but I have no choice.
Keira?
Keira, are you there?
the lady is hurt
What are you talking about? What lady?
i am lily
Calvin‚Äôs heart races.
How do you have Keira‚Äôs phone?
she dropped it
Where is she?
with me
Can you send me a picture so I can see if she‚Äôs safe?
ok
Lily sends a picture of Keira. Calvin barely keeps from throwing up.
His wife is bloodied and battered. He knows he needs to hurry.
Ten minutes later, Calvin arrives on the scene and is escorted out of a van by government officials.
He sees a sea of dead and injured people.
He studies their bodies and notices that a few have frothed at the mouth.
The virus must have spread ‚Äî that same frothing appeared in the most violent children.
As he walks through, he spots a glimmer of something gold.
He bends over and picks it up, and then drops it as if it were on fire.
It‚Äôs a cufflink he gave Doug for his birthday.
But he doesn‚Äôt have time to grieve. He texts his contact at the FBI.
It‚Äôs a virus.
Are you certain?
Positive.
That means we need to keep working on an anti-virus to protect people.
I need your help.
You need our help?
This catastrophe is a national disaster.
And now you‚Äôre telling us it was preventable?
That means it‚Äôs your fault.
Wouldn‚Äôt it be better to stop this thing once and for all?
You‚Äôre walking on thin ice, Mr. Piper‚Äî
I suggest you stick to your assignment.
You are to corral the remaining children. Understood?
Understood. I will as soon as I find my wife.
You have one hour.
Calvin uses one of the secret tunnels to get in the basement. He hears humming‚Äî
Almost like a lullaby ‚Äî and follows it, creeping towards the room with the cages.
Keira is in one of the cages and Lily is outside, opening a can of food.
She‚Äôs trying to help Keira‚Ä¶
So maybe there is a cure after all. Lily is showing empathy‚Äî
Even though her test scores proved she was one of the most dangerous children in the program.
Cautiously, Calvin approaches them. He speaks softly.
Hey, Lily.
Lily glares at Calvin, holding a can opener in front of her as a weapon.
The lady is hurt.
Keira groans and Calvin jerks to attention.
His wife is alive.
It‚Äôs okay. He‚Äôs trying to help.
I am. And you did a great job helping also, Lily. Can you keep helping us?
Lily‚Äôs lips twist by the corner. She still holds the can opener in front of her.
No cages?
Calvin hesitates. Without the help of a cage, their odds of survival aren‚Äôt high.
But there‚Äôs no choice.
No cages. I promise.
Lily thinks before setting down the can opener.
I‚Äôll get my friends.
Calvin smiles. She called the other children her friends‚Äî
Treatment IS working.
He scrambles to the cage, opens the door, and pulls Keira out.
She‚Äôs so weak.
I‚Äôm sorry.
I‚Äôm sorry, I‚Äôm sorry. I‚Äôm so, so sorry.
Cal, I‚Äôm sorry too. What‚Äôs going to happen now?
Truthfully, I don‚Äôt know. I guess it‚Äôs up to Lily.
In the hallway, there is noise.
Calvin helps Keira to her feet, putting an arm around her waist for support.
He leads her towards the mouth of the boiler room.
Lily is there with the other children‚Äî
They‚Äôre cut, dirty, and some are covered in blood.
I‚Äôm going to get you help.
No cages?
No cages. I promise.
With Lily in the lead, they walk behind the children down one of the tunnels.
At the end, they can see the back of an open truck.
Militia line the walls in full riot gear.
Lily hesitates before looking at Keira.
It‚Äôll be okay.
Lily nods and then climbs into the truck.
Behind her, the rest of the children board.
Calvin rubs the back of his neck, watching them.
There‚Äôs something that‚Äôs been worrying me even more than this.
What‚Äôs that?
Did you ever figure out who was texting you from that restricted number?
No. Does that mean it wasn‚Äôt your contact who was supposed to pick me up?
No. It wasn‚Äôt. So‚Ä¶should we worry about this guy?
Keira snorts.
Considering he pretended he was you?
Yeah, I think we should be concerned.
I don‚Äôt get it though. Why would anyone pretend to be me?
What‚Äôs his angle?
I have no idea, but he‚Äôs good.
I really thought it was you. If you hadn‚Äôt texted me when you did‚Ä¶
She takes a shaky breath.
Well, that doesn‚Äôt matter. You did text me.
It‚Äôs just scary having no idea who he is, or what his endgame is.
At least we‚Äôre here with each other. We can face our fears together.
Yeah, and look what we‚Äôre doing.
Keira gestures with her free hand to the truck as militia start to close the back door.
Lily stares at her, blatantly scared although her expression is trusting.
We‚Äôre just like the Pied Piper.
Calvin pulls Keira tightly against his chest.
He rests his chin on the top of her head.
As the taillights flash on and the truck starts to move, he speaks to her softly.
No, we‚Äôre not.
Out of the corner of his eye, he catches a glint of gold.
Doug‚Äôs cufflink ‚Äî the same one he found before.
His stomach knots up.
Calvin?
She follows Calvin's gaze.
I‚Äôm so sorry.
He didn‚Äôt deserve this.
Calvin‚Ä¶he was really quick to throw you under the bus.
That wasn‚Äôt throwing me under the bus.
She holds out her phone.
Look at the texts he sent me.
I don‚Äôt need to look. In our line of work there are layers of deception.
So you knew he‚Äôd betray you?
It‚Äôs not betrayal. It‚Äôs survival for the cause. I might have done the same if I were in his shoes.
As Calvin stoops over to pick up the cufflink, and then takes a closer look at the truck.
Army troops are following it on foot.
One soldier looks over his shoulder and smiles at them.
He seems so familiar‚Äî
Like one of the allies Doug introduced him to.
‚ÄúYou can trust him,‚Äù he remembers Doug saying. ‚ÄúHe‚Äôs just like us.‚Äù
Calvin pulls Keira to his chest, squeezing her tighter than he had before.
I swear, Keira, we‚Äôll make sure these children actually go home.
